>   (sji) wrote:
>> Russel wrote (>):
>>
> [...]
>>>More interestingly, I recall from my undergraduate days that hexagonal
>>>grids were required for CAs to simulate fluid flow, regular square
>>>lattices just don't cut the mustard.
>>
>>
>> Yes. Wolfram used a hexagonal grid, each hexagon in turn divided into 6
>> trialges.  Does anybody know why it is necessary to use hexagonal
>> lattices
>> to simulate turbulence?
>>
>> Sung
>>
> well, just based on intuition: the turbulence seems to be (after all)
> the excited rotational states of the mol. conglomerats or clusters
> driven by local or distributed power sources, and so mostly rotational
> degrees of freedom are involved.   Thus, the hexagonal (or, better,
> higher polygonal) lattices are the natural candidates to build the
> rotational states. The lattices with a spherical elementary cell seem to
> be even better candidates. Various spatial scales in the turbulence
> patterns probably can be assigned to the mol. clusters of different
> radii and/or clusters in different (higher) rotational states.
> Discreteness of cluster shapes/forms seems to be the result of
> discreteness of rotational states of the clusters.  THis is a
> speculation, though...
> turbulent-ly y'rs,
> val
